00:02:12.829 --> 00:02:15.120
I'm in the neighborhood,
talking at NASA Ames tomorrow.

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:17.640
And I thought I'd come here
because actually, Google played

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:19.544
a role, as you'll see later on.

00:02:19.544 --> 00:02:21.710
It plays such a role in all
of our lives, of course,

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:25.260
but it played a specific role
for us at the end of last year,

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:26.587
which I'll come to later on.

00:02:26.587 --> 00:02:27.920
So what I'm going to talk about?

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:31.646
I'm going to talk about the
Rosetta mission in its journey

00:02:31.646 --> 00:02:34.020
to this amazing object, which
you see in the bottom here.

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:39.275
You see much more of it called
67P Churyumov-Gerasimenko.

00:02:39.275 --> 00:02:41.400
Comets are named for the
people that discover them,

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:45.420
so it's unfortunate that Bob
Smith didn't discover this one.

00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:48.560
It's just a long name, but
these two Ukrainian astronomers

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:51.280
discovered it in 1969.

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:53.780
Of course, comets are objects
which are fascinating and have

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:55.910
been fascinating for millennia.

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:58.970
Throughout humankind, people
have looked up in the sky

00:02:58.970 --> 00:03:00.470
and seen these
strange visitors that

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:02.490
would come seemingly
out of nowhere,

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:04.860
blaze across the
sky for maybe days,

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:07.366
weeks, in some cases months.

00:03:07.366 --> 00:03:08.990
And nobody had any
idea what they were,

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:09.910
where they came from.

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:13.590
They were always thought to be
these messengers from the gods,

00:03:13.590 --> 00:03:15.430
perhaps.

00:03:15.430 --> 00:03:18.570
This idea that these
things came out of nowhere

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:21.420
unpredictably might be
portents of something bad that

00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:24.370
was about to happen.

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:26.000
We see them as
beautiful objects today.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.920
This is actually taken from
the platform of the Very Large

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:32.000
Telescope, which is an array
of four eight meter diameter

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.704
telescopes in Chile,
where my colleague here

00:03:34.704 --> 00:03:36.120
in the front row,
Hunt [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:38.900
and I have spent many years
using these telescopes to do

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:39.990
astronomy.

00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:41.545
This is astronomy
with the naked eye.

00:03:41.545 --> 00:03:43.170
You don't need an
eight meter telescope

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:46.700
to see this particular
comet, Comet McNaught.

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:49.690
But as I said, it goes
back thousands of years.

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:53.460
And this is actually from
1066 or just after 1066.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.120
This is the famous
Bayeaux Tapestry,

00:03:55.120 --> 00:03:59.490
which was created by the Normans
to commemorate the invasion

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:01.564
of England in 1066.

00:04:01.564 --> 00:04:03.730
This is the usually the
point where I point out this

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:05.020
is the last time it happened.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:08.410
But other people have tried.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:10.820
And what you see at the top
here is a comet, emblazoned

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:12.290
across the Bayeaux Tapestry.

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:15.329
And in Latin, it says "these
men wonder at the star."

00:04:15.329 --> 00:04:17.120
People here are looking
up and they thought

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:18.620
this was a portent of doom.

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:20.560
And of course, for
the English it was.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:22.590
For King Harold here, it
was a bit of a problem.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:24.964
For the Normans, it was portent
of good, you could argue.

00:04:24.964 --> 00:04:28.170
So, silver linings and all that.

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:31.410
But what we now know
from subsequent analyses

00:04:31.410 --> 00:04:36.140
of this particular object and
the fact that in the record

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:39.460
over 1,000 years,
this object appears

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:42.560
to have come back
every 76 years.

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:44.580
So Edmund Halley--
and you'll guess

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:46.380
what the name of
this comet is now--

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:48.780
found that there
was an apparition

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:50.489
on a regular basis of a comet.

00:04:50.489 --> 00:04:52.280
And he said, well,
maybe it's the same one.

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:52.955
And it was.

00:04:52.955 --> 00:04:54.010
It's Halley's Comet.

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:55.080
It's what we know
as Halley's comet.

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:57.820
And this was actually seen many,
many times throughout history.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.980
This is just one
of the occasions.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:03.250
The last time that it
came past was 1986.

00:05:03.250 --> 00:05:06.120
And of course 1986, we were
deep into the space age.

00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:09.382
And it was possible to actually
go there for the first time.

00:05:09.382 --> 00:05:11.090
And so the European
Space Agency launched

00:05:11.090 --> 00:05:13.980
a mission called Giotto as
part of an international fleet

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:15.510
to go and encounter Halley.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:18.550
Now Halley lives out
deep in the solar system,

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:21.410
way out beyond
the giant planets.

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:23.890
And it comes in every
76 years, accelerates

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:26.275
towards the inner solar
system, goes extremely fast

00:05:26.275 --> 00:05:28.440
through the middle,
and back out again.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:31.710
And so what we could do, what we
were capable of doing in 1986,

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:34.177
was effectively do what
anybody in this room--

00:05:34.177 --> 00:05:36.010
and I can say that with
absolute certainty--

00:05:36.010 --> 00:05:37.801
anybody in this room
would have to do this.

00:05:37.801 --> 00:05:42.260
If you wanted to have a
conversation with Usain Bolt

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:44.009
when he was running
the 100 meters,

00:05:44.009 --> 00:05:46.550
none of you in this room would
be able to run as fast as him,

00:05:46.550 --> 00:05:47.869
right?

00:05:47.869 --> 00:05:49.660
So the only way you
could do it is actually

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:52.020
stand out in front of
him as he sprinted past.

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:55.940
And you'd have maybe a couple
of milliseconds of conversation.

00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:56.820
You could do that.

00:05:56.820 --> 00:05:58.819
You could just direct
yourself to be in his path

00:05:58.819 --> 00:06:01.130
as long as you
avoid hitting him.

00:06:01.130 --> 00:06:03.650
And that's what we did
with Giotto in 1986.

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.640
As Halley swung through
the inner solar system,

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:09.430
we were able to get Giotto
to fly by at 68 kilometers

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:10.355
a second.

00:06:10.355 --> 00:06:12.730
And we had just minutes
of that encounter,

00:06:12.730 --> 00:06:15.380
the first time that a
comet was seen close up,

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:16.630
the comet nucleus.

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:17.750
And unfortunately, it's
a bit light in the room

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:19.624
so you can't quite see
very well what's here.

00:06:19.624 --> 00:06:21.430
But this is the nucleus
of comet Halley,

00:06:21.430 --> 00:06:22.989
about 15 kilometers across.

00:06:22.989 --> 00:06:25.280
And what you see, and what
was an interesting discovery

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:28.090
at that point is that comets
are actually very dark objects.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:30.870
We think of comets as being
composed of ice and dust

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:34.502
and therefore the phrase is
often used "dirty snowballs."

00:06:34.502 --> 00:06:36.460
And so you'd expect it
to be highly reflective.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:37.385
Turns out they're not.

00:06:37.385 --> 00:06:38.990
They're incredibly dark.

00:06:38.990 --> 00:06:40.960
And the surface
here is a mixture

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:43.380
of dust, which has been
lifted up from the comet

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:46.000
as the comet heats up when
it gets close to the sun.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.370
Some of that dust falls
back down onto the surface

00:06:48.370 --> 00:06:50.980
and slowly, you get
snowdrifts, if you like,

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:52.690
of dust on the surface.

00:06:52.690 --> 00:06:55.690
And also, there's organic
material in comets.

00:06:55.690 --> 00:06:57.951
So there's actually complex
carbon-bearing molecules

00:06:57.951 --> 00:06:58.450
in comets.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:07:00.810
And that makes it dark as well.

00:07:00.810 --> 00:07:03.060
Now, we're had a series
of comet missions.

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:05.680
NASA has been to several comets
and one of the most famous

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:08.140
encounters actually did
do what you shouldn't

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:13.240
do, which is it did stand right
in front of Usain Bolt in 2005,

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:14.690
the so-called Deep
Impact Mission.

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:17.720
You can tell what's
coming next, where

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:19.520
it was two spacecraft together.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:21.190
And the front
spacecraft was actually

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:25.190
set on a direct collision course
with the comet Tempel, Tempel 1

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:25.690
here.

00:07:25.690 --> 00:07:28.600
And then the second spacecraft
took pictures of that

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:30.410
as the first one impacted.

00:07:30.410 --> 00:07:32.022
And that's the outcome.

00:07:32.022 --> 00:07:33.980
Turns out, that's actually
a very small crater.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:35.800
Another mission has
going back to Tempel 1

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:39.120
since and seen the crater
left in a brief flyby.

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.520
It's a pretty small crater,
but a lot of material

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:42.340
was lifted up.

00:07:42.340 --> 00:07:44.080
But why would you
want to do this?

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:45.260
What's the point?

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:46.950
It's not just fireworks.

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:48.816
It's cool, but
what's the reason?

00:07:48.816 --> 00:07:51.800
The reason is that
the surface of comets

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:53.390
is because of
these dust covering

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.050
and these carbon-bearing
molecules is not really

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:57.415
the primordial material anymore.

00:07:57.415 --> 00:07:58.290
It's being processed.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:00.810
Every time a comet's come
through the inner solar system,

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:02.200
it's being frazzled, fried.

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:03.570
Think of it as a baked Alaska.

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:05.680
The outer surface is not
representative of what's

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:07.220
on the inside.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:09.540
And by excavating
material from underneath

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:11.810
and analyzing that
brief flash of light

00:08:11.810 --> 00:08:14.844
from the material as it's
thrown up, not only locally,

00:08:14.844 --> 00:08:16.260
but the Hubble
Space Telescope was

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:21.000
used to take data on this
comet during this impact.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.270
You can try to understand
what the comet's made

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:24.749
of on the inside.

00:08:24.749 --> 00:08:25.790
And why is that relevant?

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:28.820
Well, it's because comets
are leftover material

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:32.120
from the birth of our solar
system 4.6 billion years ago.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:34.320
We have this kind
of overview here

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.460
of the cycle of life
of stars and planets,

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:40.250
which starts with very
high mass stars generating

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:42.730
the heavy elements in their
course through nuclear fusion,

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:46.060
through supernovae returning on
winds, returning that material

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:47.550
to the interstellar medium.

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:51.290
That kind of mills around in a
galaxy for millions or hundreds

00:08:51.290 --> 00:08:52.910
of millions of years
but then slowly

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:56.710
gets reincorporated into dust
clouds, which can then collapse

00:08:56.710 --> 00:08:58.730
down to form new stars.

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:00.990
Those stars form
in swirling disks.

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:04.080
And around those stars
you have protoplanets.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:05.530
They form as well.

00:09:05.530 --> 00:09:06.680
You get planets like us.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:09.020
But you still get lot
of leftover material--

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:12.125
the asteroids and the comets
and lots of small dust particles

00:09:12.125 --> 00:09:14.720
as well, leftover stuff.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:17.110
And that's important, because
some of that leftover stuff

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:22.154
may have played a key role
in us on this planet today.

00:09:22.154 --> 00:09:24.070
One of the models for
the way the Earth formed

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:27.510
is that it was extremely hot
when it was young, and so hot

00:09:27.510 --> 00:09:29.864
on the surface it
couldn't retain any water.

00:09:29.864 --> 00:09:31.405
So one of the big
questions is, where

00:09:31.405 --> 00:09:33.487
does the water come
from that we drink

00:09:33.487 --> 00:09:35.820
and that we're made of, and
all the water on the planet?

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:38.120
If it wasn't on the surface
shortly after the birth

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:40.190
of the solar system,
was it delivered

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:42.330
from somewhere else later on?

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:44.750
And comets could be a very
important vector for that,

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:48.590
because they lock up ice and
dust in the outer solar system.

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:51.520
And those objects and then come
into the inner solar system

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:55.170
through perturbations and
impact on the planets.

00:09:55.170 --> 00:09:57.057
You need about
100 million comets

00:09:57.057 --> 00:09:58.640
to get the water we
have on the Earth.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:00.380
That sounds like
a lot of impacts.

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:03.670
But over half a billion years
in the early solar system,

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.080
that's not so often.

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:08.020
There were lots
of comets around.

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:10.340
So investigating comets
to try to understand

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:13.430
whether the water in comets
is the same as the water we

00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:17.870
have on the Earth is a
clue to our own origins

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:19.540
in terms of water.

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:21.810
But more than that,
the complex molecules

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:24.110
which are in comets
also, we know

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:27.110
that comets contain
amino acids, for example.

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:30.370
Interstellar space is rich
in carbon-bearing molecules.

00:10:30.370 --> 00:10:33.350
And maybe-- again, because it
was hot when it was young--

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:36.345
maybe the comets brought that
organic material to the Earth.

00:10:36.345 --> 00:10:39.080
Not life, but organic
material, which could then

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:40.490
be the building blocks of life.

00:10:40.490 --> 00:10:43.650
So we could, in some ways,
literally be comet stuff.

00:10:43.650 --> 00:10:46.440
You've heard from Carl Sagan
that we're star stuff, yes.

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:48.280
But later in the circuit,
we could actually

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:49.960
be comet stuff as well.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:53.360
And so by going to a comet and
investigating it in detail, not

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:55.890
just a brief flyby,
we may learn much more

00:10:55.890 --> 00:10:57.580
about our own origins.

00:10:57.580 --> 00:11:00.430
So I'm going to stop briefly
here and show you a five minute

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:05.060
film which we put together
last year from a completely

00:11:05.060 --> 00:11:06.840
different perspective,
to try to open up

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:11.220
this story about our own
origins, where we came from,

00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:12.960
the role that comets
might have played.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:15.050
And we did it-- we wanted
to reach the general public,

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:17.216
so we did it through the
medium of a science fiction

00:11:17.216 --> 00:11:19.480
film, which was novel.

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:21.670
NASA called us up afterwards
and said, how the hell

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:22.660
did you do that?

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:25.075
We want to do that too.

00:11:25.075 --> 00:11:26.450
Which doesn't
often happen to us.

00:11:26.450 --> 00:11:29.222
It usually goes the
other way around.

00:11:29.222 --> 00:11:30.180
So I'll show it to you.

00:11:30.180 --> 00:11:31.420
And it's something
which is a word which

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:33.670
I'm sure this company and
many other people I speak to

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:35.390
are well aware of.

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:38.465
The film is called "Ambition."

00:11:38.465 --> 00:11:42.425
