00:58:32.190 --> 00:58:33.360
appears in this summary.

00:58:33.360 --> 00:58:36.264
This is what happened
on the 12th of November.

00:58:36.264 --> 00:58:37.180
[BEGIN VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:58:37.180 --> 00:58:41.520
-Over 10 years has passed since
Rosetta and Philae launched

00:58:41.520 --> 00:58:44.864
on their exciting
mission to comet 67P,

00:58:44.864 --> 00:58:45.780
Churyumov-Gerasimenko.

00:58:48.450 --> 00:58:51.980
After three months investigating
the comet from orbit,

00:58:51.980 --> 00:58:55.200
it was time to send
Philae to its surface.

00:58:55.200 --> 00:58:59.610
A long night of final
preparations lay ahead of them.

00:58:59.610 --> 00:59:04.160
Finally, the moment everyone
had been waiting for arrived.

00:59:04.160 --> 00:59:07.030
As the world held
its breath, Rosetta

00:59:07.030 --> 00:59:09.640
moved into the exact
position needed

00:59:09.640 --> 00:59:13.200
to make sure Philae would
reach the landing site

00:59:13.200 --> 00:59:15.140
that scientists on
Earth had picked

00:59:15.140 --> 00:59:17.070
up earlier in the mission.

00:59:17.070 --> 00:59:21.420
Philae and Rosetta were sad to
be going their separate ways,

00:59:21.420 --> 00:59:23.730
but excited at the same time.

00:59:23.730 --> 00:59:26.900
Because this is what they
had been waiting to do.

00:59:26.900 --> 00:59:29.790
Philae was away.

00:59:29.790 --> 00:59:33.020
It would take seven hours
to reach the surface,

00:59:33.020 --> 00:59:37.460
but Philae wanted to get started
on his measurements right away.

00:59:37.460 --> 00:59:41.430
He could soon see the
surface in incredible detail.

00:59:41.430 --> 00:59:43.805
And the moment he
had been dreaming of

00:59:43.805 --> 00:59:45.980
had finally arrived.

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:50.210
He had reached the
surface of the comet.

00:59:50.210 --> 00:59:52.680
But all was not right.

00:59:52.680 --> 00:59:55.260
His harpoons did not fire.

00:59:55.260 --> 00:59:58.820
Philae realized he
couldn't relax yet.

00:59:58.820 --> 01:00:01.870
He was rising from
the surface again.

01:00:01.870 --> 01:00:06.830
Philae was scared he might
drift off the comet completely.

01:00:06.830 --> 01:00:08.325
This was not in the plan.

01:00:10.930 --> 01:00:13.862
But eventually, he
came back down again.

01:00:18.110 --> 01:00:21.430
However, as he looked
around, he realized

01:00:21.430 --> 01:00:26.600
he had landed in a completely
unexpected location.

01:00:26.600 --> 01:00:30.710
Philae immediately set to
work on studying his new home.

01:00:30.710 --> 01:00:34.860
It took him just over two days
to conduct all the experiments

01:00:34.860 --> 01:00:36.870
he had brought with him.

01:00:36.870 --> 01:00:41.040
After all his hard work,
Philae began to feel tired,

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:44.870
so he made sure to send all
the data he had collected back

01:00:44.870 --> 01:00:46.450
to Rosetta.

01:00:46.450 --> 01:00:49.700
As the sun set over
Philae's new home,

01:00:49.700 --> 01:00:53.640
he fell into a deep sleep,
safe in the knowledge

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:57.080
that he did his main job
well and that his family

01:00:57.080 --> 01:01:01.930
of comet-chasing heroes would
be proud of his achievement.

01:01:01.930 --> 01:01:02.960
Who knows?

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:07.400
Perhaps one day, enough sunlight
would fall on his new landing

01:01:07.400 --> 01:01:12.570
site and wake him up so that
he could carry on investigating

01:01:12.570 --> 01:01:15.466
this incredible world.

01:01:15.466 --> 01:01:20.100
And so, as the comet moved
over closer to the sun,

01:01:20.100 --> 01:01:24.280
Rosetta prepared for the next
part of her exciting adventure.

01:01:29.538 --> 01:01:30.972
[APPLAUSE]

01:01:30.972 --> 01:01:34.800
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:37.530
So the big question is,
where is Philae today?

01:01:37.530 --> 01:01:40.460
We actually don't know.

01:01:40.460 --> 01:01:42.850
It's up against
the shaded region.

01:01:42.850 --> 01:01:44.950
We know pretty
clearly where it is.

01:01:44.950 --> 01:01:45.797
It's flown over.

01:01:45.797 --> 01:01:47.380
You can actually see
the two red dots.

01:01:47.380 --> 01:01:48.879
The first one at
the top left corner

01:01:48.879 --> 01:01:50.370
is where we touched down.

01:01:50.370 --> 01:01:52.250
The second one is
the cliff we hit.

01:01:52.250 --> 01:01:53.620
And we know we're roughly here.

01:01:53.620 --> 01:01:55.620
In fact, we've refined
this a little bit better.

01:01:55.620 --> 01:01:58.526
We do this through the
tomography ranging experiments

01:01:58.526 --> 01:01:59.150
with the comet.

01:01:59.150 --> 01:02:01.150
We know the timing
very accurately.

01:02:01.150 --> 01:02:03.124
So we believe we're
somewhere in this region.

01:02:03.124 --> 01:02:05.290
But you can see, there are
lots of little white dots

01:02:05.290 --> 01:02:06.190
everywhere.

01:02:06.190 --> 01:02:08.200
And we've been looking
at all the images.

01:02:08.200 --> 01:02:11.460
Philae's roughly one or two
pixels in size at the closest

01:02:11.460 --> 01:02:14.330
pictures we have-- incredibly
difficult to actually sort out.

01:02:14.330 --> 01:02:17.420
We'll have a post out next
week showing a little bit

01:02:17.420 --> 01:02:20.110
about that, where
we think we are.

01:02:20.110 --> 01:02:22.420
But we haven't definitively
identified Philae.

01:02:22.420 --> 01:02:24.584
We're waiting for
the sun to increase,

01:02:24.584 --> 01:02:27.000
because as we get closer to
the sun, the energy increases,

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:29.340
we may recharge
Philae's batteries.

01:02:29.340 --> 01:02:31.530
It may come back to
life this summer.

01:02:31.530 --> 01:02:32.470
We're listening out.

01:02:32.470 --> 01:02:34.060
We're hoping to hear from it.

01:02:34.060 --> 01:02:35.660
At the moment, we haven't.

01:02:35.660 --> 01:02:37.077
Just to show you
what we're really

01:02:37.077 --> 01:02:38.868
doing in studying the
surface of the comet,

01:02:38.868 --> 01:02:41.390
this is an amazing image taken
during a very close flyby

01:02:41.390 --> 01:02:42.730
on Valentine's Day.

01:02:42.730 --> 01:02:45.350
We flew six kilometers
above the surface.

01:02:45.350 --> 01:02:48.590
And again, you see these
incredible structures

01:02:48.590 --> 01:02:53.130
and incredibly diverse terrain
in terms of mesas and plateaus

01:02:53.130 --> 01:02:55.499
and dust and boulders.

01:02:55.499 --> 01:02:56.415
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:02:56.415 --> 01:02:58.900
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: No,
crack's up around the neck.

01:02:58.900 --> 01:03:01.520
But if you actually
look in more detail,

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:03.620
you get to see some
very interesting things

01:03:03.620 --> 01:03:06.420
as we zoom in.

01:03:06.420 --> 01:03:08.807
And the highest res picture
that we've released so far

01:03:08.807 --> 01:03:10.890
is actually taken just
from about eight kilometers

01:03:10.890 --> 01:03:12.154
above the surface.

01:03:12.154 --> 01:03:14.070
And this is with the sun
right behind the back

01:03:14.070 --> 01:03:14.950
of the spacecraft.

01:03:14.950 --> 01:03:16.491
So you don't see
many of the shadows.

01:03:16.491 --> 01:03:19.150
And in fact, what you
do see is Rosetta.

01:03:19.150 --> 01:03:23.720
It's Rosetta's his own shadow,
from six kilometers up--

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:24.740
eight kilometers up.

01:03:24.740 --> 01:03:26.990
And so we're in this position
now where we investigate

01:03:26.990 --> 01:03:28.760
things absolutely
astonishing, sort

01:03:28.760 --> 01:03:31.960
of [INAUDIBLE] alien landscape.

01:03:31.960 --> 01:03:34.604
I mean, this is kind of science
fiction from the 1950s in terms

01:03:34.604 --> 01:03:35.270
of the pictures.

01:03:35.270 --> 01:03:36.930
And it really looks like this.

01:03:36.930 --> 01:03:39.130
But more importantly
for us now is it's

01:03:39.130 --> 01:03:41.790
starting to look like this.

01:03:41.790 --> 01:03:43.380
Every day we take
a picture of it,

01:03:43.380 --> 01:03:45.360
we are seeing more
and more jet activity,

01:03:45.360 --> 01:03:46.620
more material flowing away.

01:03:46.620 --> 01:03:49.810
This is the material which then
comes out tens of thousands

01:03:49.810 --> 01:03:52.200
of kilometers away,
flows out into the tail,

01:03:52.200 --> 01:03:55.100
which we should then be able
to see behind the comet.

01:03:55.100 --> 01:03:55.990
I hesitated there.

01:03:55.990 --> 01:03:58.520
We won't be able to see this
comet naked eye from the Earth.

01:03:58.520 --> 01:04:00.250
It's never going to
be bright enough.

01:04:00.250 --> 01:04:02.450
25 centimeter
telescope will do it.

01:04:02.450 --> 01:04:03.620
But you don't need that.

01:04:03.620 --> 01:04:04.480
We're there.

01:04:04.480 --> 01:04:06.281
We're actually there.

01:04:06.281 --> 01:04:08.030
And just one last
picture before I finish.

01:04:08.030 --> 01:04:10.270
This is one we
released last week.

01:04:10.270 --> 01:04:13.620
Over a space of three minutes,
we saw a jet come out,

01:04:13.620 --> 01:04:15.440
two pictures, three
minutes apart.

01:04:15.440 --> 01:04:17.050
And we see jet emission.

01:04:17.050 --> 01:04:19.565
So we're really in this
fantastic phase now.

01:04:19.565 --> 01:04:21.690
We'd love for Philae to
wake up, but you know what?

01:04:21.690 --> 01:04:23.040
It doesn't matter.

01:04:23.040 --> 01:04:25.340
We have Rosetta there,
doing amazing things.

01:04:25.340 --> 01:04:26.770
So let me wind up.

01:04:26.770 --> 01:04:29.180
We're at this point now where
we're actually flying by.

01:04:29.180 --> 01:04:31.262
We're learning to
live with this comet.

01:04:31.262 --> 01:04:33.220
The closest approach,
what's called perihelion,

01:04:33.220 --> 01:04:35.480
is on the 13th of August.

01:04:35.480 --> 01:04:37.560
That's the date at
which-- nothing really

01:04:37.560 --> 01:04:40.320
happens, apart from the
closest point to the sun.

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:42.410
We are currently funded
to the end of this year,

01:04:42.410 --> 01:04:44.720
but we think we should
be no problem continuing.

01:04:44.720 --> 01:04:48.404
We have enough fuel on board
to run until late next year.

01:04:48.404 --> 01:04:50.320
But as you think about
it, we'll be coming out

01:04:50.320 --> 01:04:51.780
of the solar system again.

01:04:51.780 --> 01:04:54.210
So we have to choose-- do
we go back into hibernation?

01:04:54.210 --> 01:04:55.550
Nobody likes that idea.

01:04:55.550 --> 01:04:57.990
So actually, what we're
currently investigating

01:04:57.990 --> 01:05:01.740
is whether we can land
Rosetta on the surface

01:05:01.740 --> 01:05:03.184
and have it all over again.

01:05:03.184 --> 01:05:04.600
The only problem
is, of course, we

01:05:04.600 --> 01:05:06.310
won't have another
spacecraft to talk to.

01:05:06.310 --> 01:05:09.090
So once Rosetta hits
the ground, it's over.

01:05:09.090 --> 01:05:11.900
But it will be a
fun day, I think.

01:05:11.900 --> 01:05:15.360
Lots of social media--
all the good stuff there.

01:05:15.360 --> 01:05:17.750
And it's not over.

01:05:17.750 --> 01:05:21.070
And let me end by thanking you
for letting me come and take

01:05:21.070 --> 01:05:22.530
your time today.

01:05:22.530 --> 01:05:25.450
Everybody else watching out
there, thanks very much.

01:05:25.450 --> 01:05:28.320
But I'm just standing in front
of a mission of thousands

01:05:28.320 --> 01:05:30.387
of people across Europe,
across the world.

01:05:30.387 --> 01:05:31.470
United States is involved.

01:05:31.470 --> 01:05:33.180
NASA's involved.

01:05:33.180 --> 01:05:36.350
A lot of people have
become involved making

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:38.000
movies and all sorts of stuff.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:40.570
Lots of big media--
and my communications

01:05:40.570 --> 01:05:43.900
team, who've done a lot of
the stuff you've seen here.

01:05:43.900 --> 01:05:45.400
They made it just
a privilege for me

01:05:45.400 --> 01:05:47.230
to be here today and
say, thank you very much

01:05:47.230 --> 01:05:48.190
and keep watching the mission.

01:05:48.190 --> 01:05:48.690
Thank you.

01:05:48.690 --> 01:05:52.546
[APPLAUSE]

01:06:01.989 --> 01:06:05.410
AUDIENCE: One question regarding
the satellites-- so obviously,

01:06:05.410 --> 01:06:08.467
changes during the orbits--

01:06:08.467 --> 01:06:10.550
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Rosetta
flying around the comet?

01:06:10.550 --> 01:06:13.180
AUDIENCE: No, the comet
flying around the sun.

01:06:13.180 --> 01:06:16.090
You didn't comment on how
it would feel for a human

01:06:16.090 --> 01:06:17.830
if you were standing there.

01:06:17.830 --> 01:06:20.035
Like, how bright or
dark would that be?

01:06:20.035 --> 01:06:22.310
Would it be like you were
in the middle of night?

01:06:22.310 --> 01:06:23.520
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Well,
at its closest point--

01:06:23.520 --> 01:06:24.590
AUDIENCE: What's
the lumens like?

01:06:24.590 --> 01:06:25.850
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Well,
at its closest point

01:06:25.850 --> 01:06:27.460
it's between the Earth and Mars.

01:06:27.460 --> 01:06:33.860
So it's roughly like a sunny day
on the Earth, roughly speaking,

01:06:33.860 --> 01:06:35.810
because the atmosphere
absorbs some light.

01:06:35.810 --> 01:06:38.299
I always make this joke that
when we're out at Jupiter,

01:06:38.299 --> 01:06:40.840
we don't have enough power to
run the solar panels and so on.

01:06:40.840 --> 01:06:43.165
Actually, Jupiter the
sunlight intensity

01:06:43.165 --> 01:06:47.090
is roughly the same as a typical
British summer day under cloud.

01:06:47.090 --> 01:06:50.410
So we have an enormous dynamic
range in sunlight on the Earth,

01:06:50.410 --> 01:06:51.730
whether it's cloudy or not.

01:06:51.730 --> 01:06:53.110
But it would be cold,
of course, because you

01:06:53.110 --> 01:06:54.490
would be radiating to space.

01:06:54.490 --> 01:06:56.645
You've got a cold object
next to you as well.

01:06:56.645 --> 01:07:00.070
AUDIENCE: One short one-- where
does the outgassing start?

01:07:00.070 --> 01:07:02.600
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Well,
we see it happening

01:07:02.600 --> 01:07:04.130
from many parts of the surface.

01:07:04.130 --> 01:07:05.847
We see it specifically
in certain areas.

01:07:05.847 --> 01:07:07.430
AUDIENCE: Apart from
the sun, I meant.

01:07:07.430 --> 01:07:08.305
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Oh.

01:07:08.305 --> 01:07:10.820
We saw it, actually, already
at three astronomical units.

01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:13.111
The astronomical unit is the
distance between the Earth

01:07:13.111 --> 01:07:15.880
and the sun, 150
million kilometers.

01:07:15.880 --> 01:07:19.320
We saw that initial outburst--
actually at more like 3

01:07:19.320 --> 01:07:20.237
and 1/2 AU.

01:07:20.237 --> 01:07:23.320
So activity can
happen at any time.

01:07:23.320 --> 01:07:28.860
It depends very much on
a particular fortuitous

01:07:28.860 --> 01:07:31.800
orientation with respect
to accumulated sunlight

01:07:31.800 --> 01:07:34.130
on a given day and maybe
a pocket of volatiles

01:07:34.130 --> 01:07:36.310
near the surface,
expanding and blowing up.

01:07:36.310 --> 01:07:39.530
So activity-- we've seen
Halley, the activity

01:07:39.530 --> 01:07:42.450
continued a long way
out after perihelion.

01:07:42.450 --> 01:07:45.520
So activity can happen, but it
goes as the square, roughly,

01:07:45.520 --> 01:07:49.460
as the distance or the inverse
square with the sunlight.

01:07:49.460 --> 01:07:51.885
And there's also
thresholds where

01:07:51.885 --> 01:07:53.385
volatiles reach
certain temperatures

01:07:53.385 --> 01:07:54.852
and suddenly get busy.

01:07:54.852 --> 01:07:56.310
So we're seeing a
lot more activity

01:07:56.310 --> 01:07:58.565
now than at the beginning.

01:07:58.565 --> 01:08:02.750
AUDIENCE: So does Philae have
cameras that can point back out

01:08:02.750 --> 01:08:04.255
in space if it wakes up?

01:08:04.255 --> 01:08:05.130
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: No.

01:08:05.130 --> 01:08:09.540
What it has on board is seven
cameras around the outside,

01:08:09.540 --> 01:08:10.670
which two are stereo.

01:08:10.670 --> 01:08:12.040
It's a stereo pair.

01:08:12.040 --> 01:08:14.270
But they look horizontally.

01:08:14.270 --> 01:08:16.210
And then it has
cameras pointing down.

01:08:16.210 --> 01:08:19.149
That having been said, we are
tilted at an angle like this,

01:08:19.149 --> 01:08:21.510
and we know that we
can see in space.

01:08:21.510 --> 01:08:23.460
When we did the
first panorama, we'd

01:08:23.460 --> 01:08:26.689
see very dark material under us
an illuminated cliff and then

01:08:26.689 --> 01:08:28.950
the sky, the point being--

01:08:28.950 --> 01:08:31.381
AUDIENCE: Philae
gets ejected because

01:08:31.381 --> 01:08:34.702
of outbursts, then when it
wake up and then [INAUDIBLE]?

01:08:34.702 --> 01:08:36.410
MARK MCCAUGHREAN:
That's always possible.

01:08:36.410 --> 01:08:38.710
I mean, we're in a
very shaded spot.

01:08:38.710 --> 01:08:40.439
One of the ironies
is that, in fact,

01:08:40.439 --> 01:08:44.529
if we had landed
on the surface, we

01:08:44.529 --> 01:08:46.660
calculated that by
March this year,

01:08:46.660 --> 01:08:49.990
we would have got too hot for
the electronics on the inside.

01:08:49.990 --> 01:08:52.470
And by actually
being in the shade,

01:08:52.470 --> 01:08:53.970
we're pretty cold
soaking, mind you.

01:08:53.970 --> 01:08:55.219
That's one of the big worries.

01:08:55.219 --> 01:08:56.910
We've been in cold
soak for a long time.

01:08:56.910 --> 01:09:00.260
The electronics may be fried
or inverse fried-- unfried,

01:09:00.260 --> 01:09:01.830
if you like-- chilled.

01:09:01.830 --> 01:09:02.840
So we don't really know.

01:09:02.840 --> 01:09:04.270
But if it does
come back to life,

01:09:04.270 --> 01:09:05.939
we may be there at
a more active phase.

01:09:05.939 --> 01:09:08.439
So this business of, will it
get ejected if there's activity

01:09:08.439 --> 01:09:10.600
locally-- it's always possible.

01:09:10.600 --> 01:09:11.810
But it's very tenuous.

01:09:11.810 --> 01:09:14.415
If you think about the
ejected material from comets,

01:09:14.415 --> 01:09:16.540
it's actually about the
same density as the Earth's

01:09:16.540 --> 01:09:18.300
atmosphere, 100 kilometers up.

01:09:18.300 --> 01:09:21.892
So it's just not like a strong
wind or anything like that.

01:09:21.892 --> 01:09:23.850
There's very little force
from the-- we see it.

01:09:23.850 --> 01:09:25.960
We sit on the solar panels.

01:09:25.960 --> 01:09:30.029
When we're close in, we actually
feel the wind blowing us

01:09:30.029 --> 01:09:31.319
and moving us around.

01:09:31.319 --> 01:09:34.254
We are able to sense that.

01:09:34.254 --> 01:09:37.930
AUDIENCE: OK, Mark, thanks
for this brilliant talk.

01:09:37.930 --> 01:09:42.029
And my question is, you
showed in the last image

01:09:42.029 --> 01:09:44.579
this jet that came up,
three second thing.

01:09:44.579 --> 01:09:45.704
So what's the origin of it?

01:09:45.704 --> 01:09:47.130
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: It's
not really understood.

01:09:47.130 --> 01:09:48.974
I mean, this is a
fairly wide field image

01:09:48.974 --> 01:09:49.890
taken from a distance.

01:09:49.890 --> 01:09:53.140
It may be there's a promontory
which just moved into sunlight

01:09:53.140 --> 01:09:56.220
as it tipped, as the
base of the comet

01:09:56.220 --> 01:09:57.650
tipped into sunlight there.

01:09:57.650 --> 01:09:58.660
Nobody knows yet.

01:09:58.660 --> 01:09:59.900
It's being looked at.

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:02.857
But we expect to start seeing
very transient effects.

01:10:02.857 --> 01:10:04.690
We know that comets,
of course, occasionally

01:10:04.690 --> 01:10:05.690
just go through big outbursts.

01:10:05.690 --> 01:10:07.520
AUDIENCE: Jets everywhere
in the universe.

01:10:07.520 --> 01:10:10.160
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: Jets
everywhere, exactly.

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:11.481
Indeed.

01:10:11.481 --> 01:10:13.230
We take this one-- no,
you've got the mic.

01:10:13.230 --> 01:10:16.110
AUDIENCE: So your best
case and scariest scenario

01:10:16.110 --> 01:10:18.300
is that the comet
breaks in half.

01:10:18.300 --> 01:10:21.447
If that happens, have you
modeled what's likely to Occur

01:10:21.447 --> 01:10:22.780
Is there risk to the spacecraft?

01:10:22.780 --> 01:10:24.530
MARK MCCAUGHREAN: It's
an interesting one.

01:10:24.530 --> 01:10:27.962
People actually think
it may not fall apart

01:10:27.962 --> 01:10:29.920
under centrifugal force,
which you would think.

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:33.220
It may actually slump
and fall together.

01:10:33.220 --> 01:10:34.700
It's all going to be very slow.

01:10:34.700 --> 01:10:37.620
The centrifugal force is
roughly the same as the gravity.

01:10:37.620 --> 01:10:41.012
So there's not going to be any
balls on the end of a string,

01:10:41.012 --> 01:10:42.970
you cut the string and
they fly off into space.

01:10:42.970 --> 01:10:45.950
It's going to be a slow
motion activity, at best.

01:10:45.950 --> 01:10:50.700
And at the moment, at least,
we're 100, 200 kilometers away,

01:10:50.700 --> 01:10:51.500
routinely.

01:10:51.500 --> 01:10:53.650
We have an issue at the
moment, interestingly,

01:10:53.650 --> 01:10:56.130
that in order to maintain
our orientation as we

01:10:56.130 --> 01:10:58.830
fly through our hyperbolic
flybys, well, always

01:10:58.830 --> 01:11:00.480
we use star trackers on board.

01:11:00.480 --> 01:11:02.390
We recognize
constellations on the sky,

01:11:02.390 --> 01:11:04.610
compare them to a
catalog on board.

01:11:04.610 --> 01:11:07.320
And as we fly through
the comet's coma now,

01:11:07.320 --> 01:11:08.840
we see dust
particles everywhere.

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:10.400
And we're seeing
too many of those.

01:11:10.400 --> 01:11:12.220
And we're confusing
them with stars.

01:11:12.220 --> 01:11:15.430
And we're not able at the moment
to fly that close to the comet.

01:11:15.430 --> 01:11:16.870
So we're still looking at this.

01:11:16.870 --> 01:11:19.620
If you know any people that have
got 10 years old assembler code

01:11:19.620 --> 01:11:24.610
expertise on star trackers--
somebody here, right?

01:11:24.610 --> 01:11:25.940
It's an issue.

01:11:25.940 --> 01:11:28.267
We're actually looking
to how we might

01:11:28.267 --> 01:11:29.850
be able to reprogram
the star tracker.

01:11:29.850 --> 01:11:31.270
It's very difficult to do.

01:11:31.270 --> 01:11:33.916
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
for the Mars Rover.

01:11:33.916 --> 01:11:35.610
AUDIENCE: What
scientific questions

01:11:35.610 --> 01:11:38.026
do you hope to answer in the
remainder of the mission?

01:11:38.026 --> 01:11:39.650
MARK MCCAUGHREAN:
Well, I think there's

01:11:39.650 --> 01:11:42.490
this issue of
overall composition,

01:11:42.490 --> 01:11:46.000
particularly of organics, this
discussion about amino acids,

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:48.330
for example.

01:11:48.330 --> 01:11:52.320
We know that on previous comets
that glycine has been seen.

01:11:52.320 --> 01:11:54.350
But glycine is an
interesting amino acid,

01:11:54.350 --> 01:11:57.290
because it's the only
one that's not handed.

01:11:57.290 --> 01:11:58.800
It's not chiral.

01:11:58.800 --> 01:12:01.330
The crucial thing is all life
on Earth is one-handedness.

01:12:01.330 --> 01:12:03.370
And if we go and we
see the comets are

01:12:03.370 --> 01:12:05.970
all handedness in their
amino acids as well,

01:12:05.970 --> 01:12:07.730
that's an interesting thing.

01:12:07.730 --> 01:12:10.250
It's unlikely to be the case.

01:12:10.250 --> 01:12:12.360
It has to do with how
life evolved on the Earth

01:12:12.360 --> 01:12:14.070
and picked one handedness
over the other.

01:12:14.070 --> 01:12:16.340
But if there's a slight
predominance of one-handedness

01:12:16.340 --> 01:12:19.190
over the other in the comets,
that would be very interesting.

01:12:19.190 --> 01:12:22.490
It's really to study the
comet's evolution over time,

01:12:22.490 --> 01:12:24.760
to try to understand
the amount of wastage,

01:12:24.760 --> 01:12:28.060
the amount of erosion that
happens during one perihelion

01:12:28.060 --> 01:12:28.990
passage.

01:12:28.990 --> 01:12:30.820
What are the structures?

01:12:30.820 --> 01:12:32.480
How does the outgassing occur?

01:12:32.480 --> 01:12:33.920
Where does it come from?

01:12:33.920 --> 01:12:36.390
Trying to understand how
comets are put together

01:12:36.390 --> 01:12:38.947
by effectively seeing them
fall apart, if you like.

01:12:38.947 --> 01:12:40.780
And we've never been
able to do that before.

01:12:40.780 --> 01:12:42.540
We've never been able
to fly with a comet

01:12:42.540 --> 01:12:45.899
over an extended period and see
the before and after changes.

01:12:45.899 --> 01:12:48.190
And we'll watch it as it
cools down as well, of course.

01:12:48.190 --> 01:12:50.160
We come out from the
sun after August,

01:12:50.160 --> 01:12:52.100
we'll see how some of
those processes reverse

01:12:52.100 --> 01:12:54.570
and how the dust settles
back down on the surface.

01:12:54.570 --> 01:12:57.070
So in that sense, it's not
the high end questions,

01:12:57.070 --> 01:12:58.574
are we made of comets stuff.

01:12:58.574 --> 01:13:00.240
But for scientists,
this is exactly what

01:13:00.240 --> 01:13:02.530
we love to do-- go
out and investigate

01:13:02.530 --> 01:13:05.600
weird and wonderful objects,
take them apart, and tell

01:13:05.600 --> 01:13:06.597
our friends about it.

01:13:06.597 --> 01:13:07.430
Thank you very much.

01:13:07.430 --> 01:13:11.380
[APPLAUSE]

